            <p>
                Made from the leaves of Lawsonia Inermis the tradion of Henna tattooing dates back to Ancient Egypt. It was said that Cleopatra used henna to adorn her body. <br />
                Because henna has natural cooling properties, people of the desert regions has been practicing henna art for centuries. Initially, as the stain faded away, it left patterns on the skin surface which led to ideas to make designs for decorative purposes.<br />
                In India henna was used about seven centuries before the Mughal invasion. Throughout time henna has been associated with special celebrations. Betrothals, weddings, the eighth month of pregnancy, the birth, the 40th day after a woman gives birth, naming ceremonies, etc. <br />
                A bride's wedding designs usually includes a hidden inscription of the groom's name on her palm. Tradition holds that the darker the stain on the palm of the bride the better the marriage and the more the love of the husband will be and if an unmarried girl receives scrapings of henna leaves from a bride, she will soon find a suitable match.
                Whatever the occasion is all necessary care is taken to ensure that the henna colour is of the darkest shade does not get off easily.
            </p>
