            <h3>Mixed Platter</h3>
            <p>
                Food has always been a weakness for the Bengalis. The gourmets of Bengal were so enthusiastic about eating that they not only prescribed the sequence of eating but they left behind plentiful texts where different Bengali food items and dishes were mentioned. There is even a deity called Annapurna who loves preparing and serving various dishes.<br />

                With its extraordinary fertile soil, Bengal produces variety of vegetables, fruits, spices and is the store house of paddy cultivation. Its rivers and lakes are inexhaustible source of different kinds of fish. Bengali meal also consists of meat and dairy products
            </p>
            <p>
                Bengali dishes are divided into four types: <br /><br />

                1.	Charbya  - food which is to be chewed<br />
                2.	Choṣhya  - food which is to be sucked<br />
                3.	Lehya - food which is to be licked<br />
                4.	Peya  - drinks
            </p>
            <p>
                Some green chillies, Bengali lime and some salt at the corner of the plate is a trademark of traditional Bengali meal serving.<br />

                For starters there will be either mashed or steamed vegetables, followed by a bitter vegetable preparation called Shukto, Shaak is a lightly cooked leafy vegetable which is served after Shukto. Then sequentially comes Dal or lentil soup served with some fried vegetables, macher jhol or fish curry, Mansho or meat, Chatni which is a sweet and tangy paste  made with every conceivable fruit and even vegetables. The meal is signed-off with liberal servings of traditional Bengali sweets and a Paan a beetle leaf flavoured with sweet spices which helps in digestion and acts as a mouth freshener.<br />

                Plain steamed Rice is the main accompaniment to all dishes. However, different types of Rice dish are made for different occasions. Polao, the Bengali version of Pilaf is traditionally cooked in occasions and compliments splendidly with Kasha Mangsho or Mutton/Lamb cooked on slow fire, in the Bengali way. Another Rice dish is Khichuri – a combination of Rice and Lentils cooked together and is an absolute must on a typical rainy day accompanied by various types of vegetable fritters. <br />

                Occasionally, Rice can be substituted by ‘Luchi’ and Radhaballavi a kind of Paratha stuffed with green Peas which pairs well with spicy potatoes, meat or even egg curry.
            </p>
            <h5><i>Come, enjoy the distinct culinary tradition of Bengal with our mothers and grandmothers from their home kitchen with us</i></h5>
